hazard analysis system for slac personnel page 1 area hazard analysis work form title mirror coating lab july 28 2008 location bldg & rm b137 r102 instructions an area hazard analysis aha is a process that is used to evaluate a work area to 1 determine the hazards that may be present 2 determine appropriate controls for these hazards and 3 provide a mechanism to communicate these hazards to someone entering the area the aha covers the facility and equipment within the facility it does not cover specific jobs tasks that may be performed in the area job task specific hazards and controls are covered by the jham process the aha should be done by the area manager in cooperation with the building manager an aha should be done once for all working areas and whenever there is a change in to the facility or regulations or the introduction of new equipment or new hazard complete instructions and supporting information is available at https www internal slac stanford edu esh slacsafety jham aha_instruction htm enter information into boxes which will expand to accommodate whatever length of text is entered once this aha is complete the area responsible person signs processes equipment in area hazards recommended controls & actions mirror coating evaporation station o hot surfaces during bake out burns o ion pump ion gauge & evaporation target hv o ln traps o electrical power o observe posted signs indicating hot parts o use proper equipment grounding and hv cables connectors o label hv connections on equipment o properly ventilate for ln boiloff o ensure electrical power cords and connectors are in good condition and properly connected to rated power source solvent usage o eye and skin injury o inhalation and ingestion risks o refer to msds for solvent hazard o employ appropriate ppe and procedures for handling o no eating at work areas where chemicals are employed o label solvent containers and properly store o properly dispose of waste o know location of nearest eye wash and